<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-05-12T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-05-12T15:00:00-05:00" n="394" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d394">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">838.00/1875: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Dunn</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-12T16:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">May 12,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>40. For General Russell:</p>
                        <p>Your despatch No. 24, April 28.<note n="4" xml:id="d394fn4">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <p>The Haitian Minister has made representations to the Secretary of State,
                            setting before him the documents of which copies were transmitted by
                            you, regarding the eligibility of Monsieur Borno. He was told that in
                            view of the decision of the Council of State regarding Borno’s
                            eligibility, which decision is apparently not subject to review by any
                            other body, the question of eligibility must be regarded as closed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>